\par\plain {\f2\fs36\b0\i0 About This Template}
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 By default, when compiled (File > Compile), this project will generate a document in the standard manuscript format for novels. The necessary settings are also provided to make it easy to compile to a paperback-style PDF for self-publishing or an EPUB or Kindle e-book.}
\par\plain \f2\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f2\fs36\b0\i0 How To Use This Template}
\par\pard\plain \li950\fi-475\sl360\slmult1\qj\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Create a new folder for each part of your novel as direct subdocuments of the Manuscript folder. Two  folders have already been created at this level for you, with the placeholder title \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Part\u8221\'94. You should rename these with the titles of the parts of your novel. For instance, Milan Kundera\u8217\'92s }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 The Unbearable Lightness of Being}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s first part is entitled \u8220\'93PART ONE: }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 Lightness and Weight}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8221\'94. In that example, you would name the part, \u8220\'93Lightness and Weight\u8221\'94 (the \u8220\'93Part One\u8221\'94 will be added during Compile). You can choose not to include these titles during the Compile process.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Create a new folder for each chapter inside the relevant \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Part\u8221\'94 folder and title each folder with the name of the chapter. If you don\u8217\'92t intend to use chapter names, just use something descriptive that tells you what the chapter is about. (You do not need to title the folders \u8220\'93Chapter One\u8221\'94 and so on, as chapter numbering will be taken care of automatically during the Compile process.) Some chapter folders have been created for you with the placeholder title \u8220\'93Chapter\u8221\'94.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Create a new text document for each scene inside the chapter folders. (Upon export, scenes will be separated with the \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93#\u8221\'94 character for standard manuscript format, or with a blank line for other formats.)}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Information about characters can be placed in the \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Characters\u8221\'94 folder, and information about locations can be placed in the \u8220\'93Places\u8221\'94 folder. (These are just regular folders that have had custom icons assigned to them using the Documents > Change Icon feature.)}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Character and setting sketch sheets have been provided for filling out information about the people and places in your novel. These are located in the \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Template Sheets\u8221\'94 folder. You should not edit the documents in the \u8220\'93Template Sheets\u8221\'94 folder directly unless you wish to change the templates (which you are free to do\hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2 you may wish to customise the sketch sheets or get rid of them entirely). Instead, to create a new character sheet, click on the Characters folder (or wherever you want to create your new character sheet) and from the Project menu, select New From Template > Character Sketch. This creates a new character sketch document for you to edit and fill in with your character details. You can create setting sketch sheets in the same way.}
