\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 There are various minor changes you can make to the settings to tweak this template so that it better suits your needs, as follows:}
\par\pard\plain \li950\fi-475\sl360\slmult1\qj\ltrch\loch \ls6\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b1\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b1\i0 Project and author name:}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0  The default book title and author name used in headers and elsewhere can be customised by going to Project > Meta-Data Settings\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8230\'85 and choosing the \u8220\'93Project Properties\u8221\'94 tab.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b1\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b1\i0 Part subtitles:}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0  If you don\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92t want to include the titles of your \u8220\'93Part\u8221\'94 folders in your compiled manuscript, go to the \u8220\'93Formatting\u8221\'94 pane in the Compile dialog and deselect \u8220\'93Title\u8221\'94 for the \u8220\'93Level 1\u8221\'94 folder item. Then click on \u8220\'93Section Layout\u8230\'85\u8221\'94 and remove the colon and space at the end of the title prefix (\u8220\'93Part <$R>\u8221\'94).}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b1\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b1\i0 Chapter subtitles: }{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 If you don\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92t want to include the names of your chapter folders below the chapter numbering text in the compiled document, go to the \u8220\'93Formatting\u8221\'94 pane in the Compile dialog and deselect \u8220\'93Title\u8221\'94 for the \u8220\'93Level 2+\u8221\'94 folder item and the \u8220\'93Level 1\u8221\'94 and \u8220\'93Level 2\u8221\'94 text items. (Conversely, if you }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 do}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0  want to include chapter titles for formats that don\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92t include them by default, tick these items.)}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b1\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b1\i0 Page header and footer: }{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 You can edit the page header in the \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Page Settings\u8221\'94 pane of the Compile dialog.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b1\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b1\i0 Page size: }{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 The \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Paperback Novel (with Parts)\u8221\'94 format is set to export to a page size of 5.06\u8221\'94 x 7.81\u8221\'94, which is one of the formats you can use with CreateSpace. You can customise this by clicking the menu button beside \u8220\'93Paper Size\u8221\'94 in the \u8220\'93Page Settings\u8221\'94 pane of Compile.}
\par\pard\plain \li950\fi-475\sl360\slmult1\qj\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b1\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b1\i0 Font}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 : You can use the \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Formatting\u8221\'94 pane in Compile to change the font used in the final document by selecting a row in the elements table, then clicking into the preview text to select it and clicking the \u8220\'93A\u8221\'94 button in the format bar to change the font settings. Note that fonts are not included in e-books, however\hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2 e-readers choose their own fonts (and you would need to pay a hefty fee for a licence to embed a particular font in an e-book).}
\par\pard\plain \li950\fi-475\sl360\slmult1\qj\ltrch\loch \ls6\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b1\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b1\i0 Making your own special folders:}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0  The \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Characters\u8221\'94 and \u8220\'93Places\u8221\'94 folders are really just regular folders that have been set up in a particular way, and you are free to create other folders that work in a similar manner.}
\par\pard\plain \li1440\fi-475\sl360\slmult1\qj\ltrch\loch \ls6\ilvl1{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i0	1.	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 To create a folder with a custom icon, add a new folder, place it where you want it, ensure it is selected, and then go to Documents > Change Icon to choose a different icon.}
\par\plain \ilvl1{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i0	2.	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 To create your own template sheets, simply create a new document inside the \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Template Sheets\u8221\'94 folder and set it up however you want (whether by adding text, changing the title, setting default meta-data, or whatever). Now this document will be available as the basis of new documents from the New From Template menu. (You can add a custom icon to this if you so wish, too.)}
\par\pard\plain \li950\fi-475\sl360\slmult1\qj\ltrch\loch \ls7\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b1\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b1\i0 Working with chapters instead of scenes:}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0  By default, this project is set up so that you write each scene as a separate text document. If you don\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92t like to break things up quite that much and would prefer to write an entire chapter in each text document, make the following changes:}
\par\pard\plain \li1440\fi-475\sl360\slmult1\qj\ltrch\loch \ls7\ilvl1{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i0	1.	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Rename the \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Scene\u8221\'94 documents to use your chapter titles and move them so that they are contained directly inside the \u8220\'93Part\u8221\'94 folders (that is, at the same level as the current \u8220\'93Chapter\u8221\'94 folders).}
\par\plain \ilvl1{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i0	2.	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Move the chapter folders to the Trash.}
\par\plain \ilvl1{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i0	3.	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Create a new text document for each chapter.}
\par\plain \ilvl1{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i0	4.	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 In the \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Separators\u8221\'94 pane of the Compile dialog, change the \u8220\'93Text separator\u8221\'94 setting to \u8220\'93Page break\u8221\'94.}
\par\plain \ilvl1{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i0	5.	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 If your scene separators are centred (for instance if you are using \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93#\u8221\'94 as the scene separator) and you want them to appear centred in the compiled document, too, select them and choose Format > Formatting > Preserve Formatting.}
\par\pard\plain \li950\fi-475\sl360\slmult1\qj\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b1\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b1\i0 Everything else:}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0  The above constitutes only the most common changes. You can completely change the output format by changing the various settings available in Compile.}
